{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9c1e4b24-f02f-48ec-821c-c26253a2e14e","content":"Yes, both are known MSTest v4 breaking changes. Here's the rundown:\n\n## 1. Lost test history in Azure DevOps\n\nMSTest v4 changed the **default test ID** to a fully-qualified name. Azure DevOps sees these as entirely new tests. Fix it by adding to your `.csproj`:\n\n```xml\n<TestIdGenerationStrategy>DisplayName</TestIdGenerationStrategy>\n```\n\nThis restores v3-compatible IDs.\n\n## 2. `TestContext.TestName` in `[ClassInitialize]`\n\nIn v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is a **class-level context** — it no longer carries test-specific properties like `TestName`. Accessing it throws. Your fix:\n\n```csharp\n[ClassInitialize]\npublic static void ClassInit(TestContext context)\n{\n    // context.TestName is not available here in v4\n    // Move test-specific logic to [TestInitialize] or\n    // use context.FullyQualifiedTestClassName instead.\n}\n```\n\n## Other key v4 gotchas to watch for\n\n| Area | Change |\n|---|---|\n| **`[DataRow]` type coercion** | Implicit conversions (e.g., `int` → `long`) that worked in v3 now fail. Match types exactly. |\n| **`Assert.AreEqual` on doubles** | Floating-point tolerance behavior is stricter. |\n| **Parallel execution** | Parallel is now **on by default** at the method level. Add `[assembly: Parallelize(Scope = ExecutionScope.ClassLevel)]` or disable it if tests aren't thread-safe. |\n| **`[DeploymentItem]`** | Behavior changed; copies may go to a different output path. |\n| **`TestContext.Properties`** | Mostly read-only now; writing custom keys may throw. |\n\nThe parallel-by-default change is especially likely to surface hidden shared-state bugs. I'd recommend auditing for that first.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2fd3ea22-97a0-4805-af95-28dacf274fbb","outputTokens":479},"id":"53b47b38-c4d0-4697-b54c-c61642288218","timestamp":"2026-04-03T01:28:44.473Z","parentId":"bcbebcc5-999f-40ff-b41c-4c49f9171164"}
